erican Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Grancey","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Pegeen.","Irish (Roscommon): variant of   Glancy  , from <b>Mag Fhlannchaidh</b> (see   Clancy  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Glancy","meanings":["Irish (Roscommon and Leitrim): shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mag Fhlannchaidh</b> ‘son of <i>Flannchadh</i>’ (see   Clancy  )."]}]},{"name":"Eude","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Judas  , occasionally used in the New Testament and elsewhere to distinguish the apostle Jude (Judas Thaddaeus), to whom one of the Epistles in the New Testament is attributed, from the traitor Judas Iscariot. It is also borne by the central character in  Thomas Hardy's  gloomy novel Jude the Obscure (  1895 ), a film adaptation of which was released in  1996 . The  Lennon  and  McCartney  song ‘Hey Jude’ (  1968 ) and the British actor  Jude Law  (  b. 1972 ) may have contributed to the popularity of the name in recent times. As a girl's name it is a short form of   Judith   or   Judy  , and is sometimes used independently."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Eude de Grancey III was born in 1198, in Grancey-le-Château, Côte-d'Or, Burgundy, France. He marrie